{
  "doc_id": "57458",
  "text": "The diagnosis of TBI is mainly based on a neurological examination of the patient, but also on imaging techniques such as computed tomography (CT) or magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) [CITATION_1] . The Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) is the most commonly used system for classifying TBI severity; a total score of 13-15 refers to mild TBI, 9-12 to moderate TBI, and 3-8 to severe TBI [CITATION_2] . CT and MRI scans often fail to detect lesions caused by injury, due to limited sensitivity and the absence of micro-bleeds; this makes the detection of severe TBI easy, but the a1111111111 a1111111111 a1111111111 a1111111111 a1111111111 detection of mild and moderate TBI more difficult [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Moreover, the GCS score has limitations in diagnosing mild TBI in the presence of polytrauma, alcohol abuse, use of sedatives, and psychological stress [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
